content.text:
I see the problem in the `useEffect` that calls `fetchMembers`:

```275:284:sheepmug_project26-main/sheepmug_main/src/app/components/pages/Members.tsx
  useEffect(() => {
    fetchFamilyGroups();
    fetchMemberRequests();

    // Only fetch members when viewType is 'members', token and selectedBranch are available and not loading auth
    if (viewType === 'members' && token && selectedBranch && !authLoading && !isLoading) {
      console.log("useEffect: Triggering fetchMembers due to token/branch/authLoading/viewType/isLoading change.");
      fetchMembers();
    }
  }, [fetchFamilyGroups, fetchMemberRequests, fetchMembers, token, selectedBranch, authLoading, viewType]);
```

The condition `!isLoading` in the `if` statement is preventing `fetchMembers` from being called initially. When the page loads, `isLoading` is `true` by default until `fetchMembers` completes. This creates a circular dependency where `fetchMembers` can never be called if `isLoading` is true, and `isLoading` will never be false if `fetchMembers` is not called.

I will remove `!isLoading` from the `useEffect`'s conditional call to `fetchMembers`. The `isLoading` state is managed *within* `fetchMembers`, so it shouldn't be a condition for *calling* it.

The purpose of `isLoading` is to show a loading spinner or disable UI elements while data is being fetched, not to prevent the fetch itself.

